07587nam a2200889Ia 9780231557696DE-B159720240602123719.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240602t20232023nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802315576967 a10.7312/asme208922doi  a(DE-B1597)673045  a(OCoLC)1401654866  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aPS659b.B47 2023 7aLAN0080002bisacsh04a818.008223/eng/2023112904aThe Best American Magazine Writing 2023 /ced. by Sid Holt. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- tAcknowledgments -- tThe Battle for Baby L. -- tShe Never Hurt Her Kids. So Why Is a Mother Serving More Time than the Man Who Abused Her Daughter? -- tAristocrat Inc. -- tMonuments to the Unthinkable -- tThe Landlord and the Tenant -- tDeath Sentence -- tThe Time to Pass Paid Leave Is Now -- tA Post- Roe Threat and The Post- Roe Era and Is Abortion Sacred? -- tWe Need to Take Away Children -- tThe Militiamen, the Governor, and the Kidnapping That Wasn’t -- tHow a Nepo Baby Is Born -- tTinder Hearted -- tAcid Church -- t“She’s Capital!” -- tViola Davis, Inside Out -- tLight and Shadow -- tWinter Term -- tUntold -- tPermissions -- tContributors0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Best American Magazine Writing 2023 offers a selection of outstanding journalism on timely topics, including inequalities and injustices pressuring families, especially mothers. Rozina Ali tells the story of a U.S. marine who unlawfully adopted an Afghan girl and her family’s efforts to bring her home (New York Times Magazine). A Mother Jones exposé confronts the imprisonment of women for failing to protect their children from their abusive partners. “The Landlord and the Tenant” juxtaposes the lives of a poor single mother convicted for her children’s deaths in a fire and the man who owned the fatal property (ProPublica with Milwaukee Journal Sentinel). Caitlin Dickerson investigates the history of the U.S. government’s family-separation policy (The Atlantic). Jia Tolentino’s New Yorker commentary considers abortion in a post-Roe world.The anthology features pieces on a wide range of subjects, such as Nate Jones on the “Nepo Baby” and Allison P. Davis’s essay about a decade on Tinder (New York). Natalie So recounts how her mother’s small computer chip company became the target of a Silicon Valley crime ring (The Believer). Clint Smith asks what Holocaust memorials in Germany can teach the United States about our reckoning with slavery (The Atlantic). Esquire’s Chris Heath examines the FBI’s involvement in a plot to kidnap the governor of Michigan. Courtney Desiree Morris takes a queer psychedelic ramble through New Orleans (Stranger’s Guide). Namwali Serpell reflects on representations of sex workers (New York Review of Books). An ESPN Digital investigation uncovers Penn State’s other serial sexual predator before Jerry Sandusky. Profiles of the acclaimed actress Viola Davis (New York Times Magazine) and the self-taught artist Matthew Wong (New Yorker), as well as Michelle de Kretser’s short story “Winter Term” (Paris Review), round out the volume.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aAmerican prose literaturey21st centuryvPeriodicals. 0aAmerican prose literature-21st century. 0aJournalismxAwardszUnited StatesvPeriodicals. 0aJournalism-Awards-United States. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Journalism.2bisacsh1 aAli, Rozina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aArmstrong, Ken, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDavis, Allison P., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/re